40|$|Previous {{research}} has found that child support receipts deter mothers' labor supply less than does other non-wage income. This paper argues that because child support is a variable income source, actual receipts may differ from unobservable <b>permanent</b> <b>receipts</b> on which hours worked are based. This introduces an errors-in-variables bias causing the estimated income effect of child support on hours worked to be biased toward zero. When one replaces actual receipts with predicted <b>permanent</b> <b>receipts,</b> such income effect is found to be statistically indistinguishable from that of other non-wage income. Copyright 1990 Western Economic Association International. ...|$|E
